<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Boost from Laidlaw helps Quicks advance to
Pounds 3m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Quicks Group, the Manchester-based motor distributor, reported a 48 per cent
increase in 1993 pre-tax profits to Pounds 3.04m yesterday, up from Pounds
2.06m the previous year.
Turnover grew by 27 per cent to Pounds 253m (Pounds 199m) almost entirely
reflecting a Pounds 52m contribution from the Laidlaw group of five Ford
main dealerships, which were acquired in July last year.
Earnings per share from the enlarged group, which now consists of 18 car
dealerships, 10 of which are Ford, increased by 22 per cent to 9.5p (7.8p)
and the final dividend is being raised to 3p (2.75p) making a 5p (4.5p)
total for the year.
Operating profits grew by 23 per cent to Pounds 4.51m (Pounds 3.66m)
including a Pounds 336,000 contribution from Laidlaw, while net interest
costs fell to Pounds 1.47m (Pounds 1.6m).
The group noted that the recovery apparent in the first half continued into
the second half with pre-tax profits, on an equivalent basis, at Pounds
1.61m compared with Pounds 950,000 for the 1992 period.
Mr Alec Murray, managing director, said that this near doubling of
second-half profits reflected the continuance of strict management controls
following the installation of the new management team in late 1991, and in
particular the profit impact of the run-down of the group's leasing
activities.
Quicks' overall new car registrations had exceeded manufacturers' targets
and the sales of used vehicles had been higher than the previous year's
total.
Despite difficult market conditions the group's service, bodywork and parts
distribution business also continued to be profitable.
Mr Murray stated that 'margins in every part of our business have remained
under pressure for the whole year', but added that 'management action to
further reduce the cost base has helped offset margin erosion.'
So far this year trading conditions had improved with registrations of both
cars and commercial vehicles ahead of last year.
'The market remains highly competitive, but it is encouraging that Ford has
begun to strengthen its position', Mr Murray said.
</TEXT>
