<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Trinity rises 32% to Pounds 19.9m - UK
newspapers contributed lion's share of turnover and profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Trinity International, the Chester-based regional newspaper publisher, made
pre-tax profits of Pounds 19.85m last year, an increase of 32 per cent on
1992's Pounds 15.09m, which was restated in accordance with FRS 3.
Operating profits jumped from Pounds 16.1m to Pounds 20.85m, including
Pounds 418,000 from acquisitions.
Mr Philip Graf, chief executive, said: 'This is our best operational
performance to date.'
Trinity, which owns daily newspapers in Liverpool and weeklies in
Merseyside, North Wales, Canada and the US, has changed tack since 1989 by
divesting from paper making and concentrating on newspaper publishing.
Last year it fully integrated Scottish and Universal Newspapers, bought in
1992, and spent Pounds 12.4m buying Huddersfield Newspapers and Pounds 23.2m
acquiring the newspaper interests of Argus Press, based in southern and
south-east England.
Turnover advanced by 16.5 per cent from Pounds 115.4m to Pounds 134.4m with
UK newspapers responsible for Pounds 79.4m - 59 per cent of sales compared
with 54 per cent.
UK newspapers also made the lion's share of profits with Pounds 15.7m, or 75
per cent of the whole.
Canadian and US operations benefited from senior management changes, new
titles and marketing initiatives, improving profit contributions to Pounds
2.99m (Pounds 1.77m) in Canada and Pounds 2.17m (Pounds 1.81m) in the US.
Mr Graf said Trinity would be trying to expand further by innovation,
product development and acquisition, but was not at present involved in
serious discussions over buying more newspapers.
Gearing rose from 14.5 per cent to 50 per cent, reflecting the latest
acquisitions.
Earnings per share show a 40 per cent rise to 20.2p (14.4p restated).
A proposed final dividend of 6.7p (6p) lifts the total by 1p to 9.7p.
COMMENT
Profitability in the regional press is notoriously dependent on local
classified advertisements for jobs, homes and second-hand cars, as well as
display advertisements by retailers. If Trinity is to keep it up, the
strength of the UK recovery will become more important as acquisitions
become harder to find. Short-term, however, Trinity has one last cost
squeeze to exploit: the Argus titles acquired in November are among the last
in western Europe where journalists still use typewriters. Moving to
computerised direct input and cutting out a stage in the production process
should yield substantial gains in productivity and profitability over the
next two or three years, though managing such change in the newspaper
industry always carries some risk of conflict and interruption to revenues.
</TEXT>
