<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Prudential lifts payout on 45% rise: Turnround at M&amp;G
reinsurance arm helps financial services company to Pounds 589m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Prudential Corporation, the financial services and life insurance company,
has reported pre-tax profits of Pounds 589m for 1993, a 45 per cent advance,
helped by a sharply improved performance in Mercantile &amp; General, its
reinsurance subsidiary.
The final dividend rose to 8.7p, pushing the total up by almost 11 per cent
to to 13.2p.
Mr Mick Newmarch, chief executive, said Prudential did not need to make
specific provisions against potential compensation claims in respect of
personal pensions sold to people transferring out of occupational schemes.
Last year it carried out some Pounds 355m pension transfer business.
Profits from the life business rose to Pounds 481m, from Pounds 444m, with
much of the increase coming from operations outside the UK. Profits from the
UK business rose just Pounds 6m to Pounds 282m.
In a sharp turnround, M&amp;G's non-life business produced a profit of Pounds 6m
in 1993, after a loss in 1992 of Pounds 143m. Mr Newmarch said this came
partly from the 'lack of catastrophes', but also from measures to correct
pricing levels, control underwriting exposure and cut costs. The full
effects would be seen this year, he said.
UK domestic insurance more than doubled profits from Pounds 27m to Pounds
55m, reflecting favourable weather and claims experience. The contribution
from Prudential's investment management rose to Pounds 23m, from Pounds 8m.
Annual premium sales of life business in the UK fell 12 per cent, though
single premium sales were up 24 per cent.
Jackson National Life, Prudential's US subsidiary, contributed profits of
Pounds 122m, though this was not directly comparable with the 1992 figure of
Pounds 86m, which included Pounds 52m related to investment gains.
Mr Newmarch said that sales of Jackson's main product - single premium
deferred annuities - had been disappointing and 38 per cent down in dollar
terms. The company has launched a new range of products and will expand into
New England this year, and open in New York.
Mr Newmarch highlighted the group's operations in southern Asia and the
Pacific as areas of future growth: it is to open offices in China and
Indonesia.
Earnings per share increased 40 per cent to 21.0p, from 15.0p.
In the alternative method of calculating life company accounts - the
accruals basis which seeks to recognise profit in the current year rather
than from business written previously - Prudential's profits rose 10 per
cent to Pounds 887m. Of this, new business represented Pounds 289m (Pounds
329m), while the investment return on shareholders' accrued interest
totalled Pounds 406m (Pounds 353m).
Prudential confirmed last night that in 1993 it sacked 23 members of staff
for misdemeanours, including falsifying customer records.
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
