FT  23 MAR 94 / Ciskei 'homeland' leaders cede power amid widespread unrest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The government of Ciskei, a nominally independent black homeland in South
Africa, last night relinquished power after widespread unrest. In the Lebowa
black homeland, the chief minister also requested assistance from Pretoria
after a civil servants' strike made it impossible to keep control.
South African troops moved into Ciskei after homeland police took senior
officers hostage claiming they had been involved in corruption. South
Africa's Foreign Affairs Ministry said Ciskei leader Brigadier Oupa Gqozo
requested assistance from Pretoria. In a statement, the ministry said:
'Brigadier Gqozo telephoned to say the situation was out of hand and there
was danger of large-scale conflict and bloodshed. He indicated he had come
to the conclusion he ought to relinquish power in an attempt to reduce the
ongoing tension.'
The multi-party Transitional Executive Council said last night that two
administrators - one from the TEC and one from the South Africa government -
would administer the Ciskei until April's elections.
Three of South Africa's 10 homelands - including Bophuthatswana, whose
government fell earlier this month - have now been removed from power. The
news from Ciskei and Lebowa will substantially increase pressure on the
KwaZulu homeland.
Zulu chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi, who heads the KwaZulu homeland, yesterday
claimed he had a secret African National Congress document that showed the
ANC also planned to topple him from power.
Also yesterday, a multi-party task force set up by the TEC said it had
uncovered evidence linking so-called 'hit squads' operating in Natal
province to the office of Chief Buthelezi. Inkatha is not represented on the
TEC, which is dominated by the ANC.
The taskforce findings will further damage Inkatha's credibility following
allegations that South African police generals gave guns to the party.
</TEXT>
