<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Leading Article: Greenspan ups interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Central banking is an art, not a science. In a country with a floating
exchange rate and little faith in monetary targeting, it is an exceptionally
difficult art at that. It is one that Mr Alan Greenspan's Federal Reserve
has practised adeptly in recent years. But events this year suggest it may
be losing its sureness of touch.
The case for raising short-term interest rates once more had become very
strong. Economic data since the surprise announcement, in early February, of
a quarter of a percentage point increase have underlined the strength of the
US economy.
Revised figures have shown the economy grew at an annual rate of 7.5 per
cent in the last quarter of 1993, rather than the 5.9 per cent first
reported. Retail spending is robust. Industrial production appears to be
growing at an annual rate of 7-8 per cent this quarter, while the jobless
rate, at 6.5 per cent, is already quite low.
In addition, monetary policy has remained expansionary. The short rate of
interest has been less than half the long rate; the absolute gap between the
two has been more than 3 1/2 percentage points; and the short-term real rate
of interest has been barely positive.
Finally, the bond market decline since the last rate increase indicates
anxieties about inflation that the Federal Reserve has failed to still. A
prudent central bank, worried about its reputation and, indeed, about the
sustainability of the recovery, would want to push bond rates down once
more.
The question then is not whether the Federal Reserve should have raised its
rates, but rather by how much. What Mr Greenspan said yesterday was merely
that the central bank would tighten reserves, an action that then increased
the federal funds rate to 3.5 per cent. In its manner and its matter, this
was the very least he could have done, particularly after last Friday's
surprise meeting with President Bill Clinton, which was bound to renew
doubts about the independence of the Federal Reserve.
Unfortunately, the Federal Reserve may not have done enough. Monetary policy
remains expansionary, while markets will still be waiting for Mr Greenspan's
next shoe to fall. It might have been wiser to put interest rates at a more
obviously 'neutral' level immediately.
If rates were 4 per cent or more, nobody would expect them to rise in the
near future and few would doubt that Mr Greenspan had already done enough.
Sometimes central banks do indeed have to feel their way. But the US in
early 1994 may need more decisive treatment.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
