<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you know any young people (and there seem to be lots) who are vague about
what, exactly, was so detestably inhuman about the Nazis, tell them to watch
today's Timewatch. Pawel Lozinski's documentary 'Birthplace' follows Henryk
Gryndberg as he returns to the village in Poland where he was born, and
moves from house to house trying to find some trace of his family or
information about how they died (8.00 BBC2).
It is followed by the last in the present series of Building Sights, USA.
Actor John Malkovich enthuses over the Chrysler Building which is easily the
most attractive in New York. At all times of the day or night, in all
conditions of light and weather, it is always exciting to catch sight of the
Chrysler down one of those urban canyons (8.45).
The Underworld shows how the middle class drug dealers of the 1960s have
been superseded by professional criminals (9.30 BBC1). One day perhaps
television will make a programme showing how the de-criminalisation of drugs
would, at one fell swoop, destroy most of the modern crime wave.
</TEXT>
