<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / TV advertising limit raised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independent Television Commission has decided that television
advertising sales houses will be allowed to sell airtime for TV companies up
to a limit of 25 per cent of UK television advertising revenue.
The current limit, set more than three years ago, is 25 per cent of ITV
revenue.
The liberalisation follows the line adopted by the Office of Fair Trading
when it considered the advertising sales implications of the recent spate of
ITV takeovers.
The takeovers were not to be referred to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission as long as by August 1995 none of the sales houses accounted for
more than 25 per cent of total television advertising sales.
Mr Frank Willis, ITC director of advertising and sponsorship, said yesterday
that action was being taken because 'we are conscious that Pounds 2bn of
business will be done between now and August 1995. We have a regulatory
responsibility and believe that people should not feel they can do what they
like between now and 1995'.
</TEXT>
