<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Hunt launches drive for more skilled workers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fourteen industrial and commercial sectors were selected yesterday by Mr
David Hunt, the employment secretary, as prototypes for the government's
'modern apprenticeship scheme'.
The scheme aims to create a new generation of skilled workers.
Industry trainers in sectors including information technology, chemicals and
agriculture will work with employers and Training and Enterprise Councils -
which deliver government training - to recruit 2,000 young people in England
and Wales to be trained to technician and supervisory levels.
When fully operational next year the Pounds 1.25bn scheme will offer up to
50 per cent more public money than is now available to training
organisations. This has been made possible by a combination of declining
numbers of young people on Youth Training and a small amount of new money.
Mr Hunt said the response to the scheme from employers had been
'overwhelming'. But employers said yesterday many of them were waiting for
funding details before making formal commitments.
The Engineering Training Authority said: 'The government will have to make a
big marketing effort to get both employers and young people on board.'
It is intended that when the modern apprenticeship is fully operational up
to half of 16- to 19-year-olds on government training schemes will achieve
Level Three national vocational qualifications, the vocational equivalent of
two A levels. At present most participants on YT attain Level Two NVQs, the
vocational equivalent of four GCSEs.
The scheme forms part of the government's drive to meet national targets for
the attainment of vocational qualifications. One of these is that by 2000,
half of young people should reach NVQ Level Three or its academic
equivalent.
At present 37 per cent of young people have achieved this skill level.
Recently the employer-led National Advisory Council for Education and
Training Targets said the UK should be aiming higher.
It added: 'International comparisons point to the need to do so. In Japan 80
per cent of young people reached a comparable level in 1986.'
</TEXT>
