<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Insolvency move not ruled out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government made clear last night that it had not ruled out the
possibility of retrospective legislation to safeguard the position of
insolvency practitioners appointed as administrators and receivers to
companies in trouble.
At the same time it successfully called on the House of Lords to follow the
example of the Commons by rejecting amendments seeking to make the
Insolvency (No 2) bill effective from December 30 1986.
Peers rushed the bill through and it should receive royal assent today or
tomorrow.
The bill provides protection from Tuesday of last week for administrators
and receivers from the consequences of a Court of Appeal ruling on Paramount
Airways which, in effect, made them responsible for the contractual
employment obligations of a company after 14 days.
Lord Strathclyde, chief government spokesman on the bill, gave an assurance
to peers who warned that insolvency practitioners could face claims of up to
Pounds 1bn - possibly involving the bankruptcy of some small- and
medium-sized accountancy firms. He said ministers would closely watch how
the situation developed.
He refused to be drawn on whether the government was likely to introduce
further emergency legislation.
Lord Donaldson of Lymington, a former Master of the Rolls, criticised the
hasty manner in which parliament had been asked to approve the bill, but
insisted that it would be wrong to provide blanket retrospection. He
suggested that it would have been more satisfactory if it had been delayed
for a week to enable the main 1986 Insolvency Act to be amended.
Lord Donaldson suggested that a provision should be introduced requiring
insolvency practitioners to inform each employee of the company concerned
whether they were adopting or disclaiming employees' contracts.
He had not introduced such a provision 'because I am not certain of my
ability to amend the bill on the hoof'.
</TEXT>
