<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Debts of Labour councils attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Curry, the local government minister, yesterday said debt-ridden
Labour councils were a 'national disgrace' as the campaign for May's local
elections continued to stress financial issues.
Mr Curry said 18 of the 20 English councils with the highest debt were
Labour-controlled. Brent, the only Conservative council on the list, had
been Labour-controlled until 1990.
The Conservatives printed a league table comparing Labour councils' debt
with third-world countries. Manchester and Birmingham, with debts of Pounds
1.326bn and Pounds 1.233bn respectively, had higher external debts than
Paraguay, Niger and Nepal.
Mr Jack Straw, Labour's local government spokesman, described Mr Curry's
claims as 'an embarrassing own-goal', saying that the UK's current borrowing
 -Pounds 50bn in one year - was more than China had borrowed in 50 years.
Mr Curry said local authority debt could not be compared with the public
sector borrowing requirement because it did not have to perform
'macroeconomic policy'. He said local government finance should be directed
at 'extremely well-defined statutory res-ponses'.
Mr David Thomas, head of local government for the Chartered Institute of
Public Finance and Accountancy, suggested that local authority debt did not
necessarily reflect poor management. 'Local authority debt is really there
because that authority has responded to need.'
He added that it could only be accumulated for capital spending
requirements, rather than day-to-day revenue expenditure.
He added, however, that the 21 debt-free councils would have more
flexibility to use capital receipts. According to Mr Curry's figures only
one of these is Labour while 10 are Conservative and two are Liberal
Democrat.
Mr Curry announced that the government would make no further announcements
on counties so far affected by the local government review until after the
May elections.
</TEXT>
