<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Channel 5 television 'should be digital'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Plans to launch television channels using existing technology should be
frozen until a full analysis can be carried out of the economics of digital
television, a report being published today suggests.
Mr Dermot Nolan, a director of Convergent Decisions Group, a new
consultancy, argues that the launch of a new Channel 5 service in the UK
using present analogue technology would be trapped in 'a twilight era'.
Mr Nolan, who until recently specialised in digital broadcasting and
tele-communications issues at consultants Coopers &amp; Lybrand, says digital
channels - broadcast from terrestrial transmitters - will be operational in
the next five years.
The Independent Television Commission has made it clear that it wants to
readvertise a Channel 5 licence but has asked the government whether the
necessary frequencies are still available.
Both the national heritage department and the Department of Trade and
Industry are looking into the issues involved.
Mr Nolan concedes that going ahead with Channel 5 would cause very little
disruption to the roll out of digital terrestrial television.
The average number of national digital channels available would be reduced
from 10 to eight in a period when existing channels - such as BBC1 - would
still have to be transmitted in the old form. This would cater for those who
did not have digital receivers.
There is a growing belief in industrialised countries that the radio
spectrum is a vital resource and that it is inefficient to use it for
analogue rather than digital television.
Mr Nolan says: 'A fundamental overhaul of broadcasting and
telecom-munications legislation is now required to retain UK competitiveness
in broad-casting and telecommuni-cations, in order to exploit the benefits
of digital television.'
</TEXT>
