<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / TV advertising limit is raised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independent Television Commission has decided that television
advertising sales houses will be allowed to sell airtime for TV companies up
to a limit of 25 per cent of total UK television advertising revenue.
The current limit, set more than three years ago, is 25 per cent of ITV
revenue.
The liberalisation follows the line adopted by the Office of Fair Trading
when it considered the advertising sales implications of the recent spate of
ITV takeovers, such as the Carlton Communications purchase of Central.
The takeovers were not to be referred to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission as long as by August 1995 none of the sales houses accounted for
more than 25 per cent of total television advertising sales.
Mr Frank Willis, ITC director of advertising and sponsorship, said yesterday
that action was being taken immediately because 'we are conscious that
Pounds 2bn of business will be done between now and August 1995. We have a
regulatory responsibility and believe that people should not feel they can
do what they like between now and 1995.'
ITC consent will still be needed on most ITV sales operations and a single
organisation will not be allowed to sell both ITV and Channel 4.
The commission is seeking views on two outstanding issues - whether there
should be flexibility around the 25 per cent threshold and the future
treatment of Channel 5.
</TEXT>
