<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Bar is again accused of race bias
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fresh allegations of racial discrimination were levelled at the Bar last
night over its new system for selecting students for the barristers' finals
course.
The new system, based on a mixture of academic qualifications and
psychometric tests, has resulted in just 91 places on next year's finals
course being offered to black and ethnic minority candidates out of a total
of 882.
Mrs Justice Booth, chairman of the Bar school's central selection board,
defended the system as 'fair and valid'. All answers to the tests which were
based on skills identified by psychometric researchers as required by
barristers were double marked blind, she said. Markers had no access to
information about the gender or ethnic origin of can-didates.
But Mr Makbool Javaid, chairman of the Society of Black Lawyers, said the
results were clearly discriminatory. He said: 'It cannot be the case that
such a low percentage of black and ethnic minority candidates are judged fit
and suitable to become barristers.'
Mr Javaid, a solicitor, said the society had warned the Bar last year that
the tests had the potential for bias and that it would consider seeking
judicial review of the results.
Women also fared badly under the new system. Out of 2,290 applicants, 1,764
were white, 481 black (45 did not disclose their ethnic origin) and 922 were
women. Of the 882 offers made, 774 were to white candidates, 91 to black or
ethnic minority candidates and 17 to those who did not disclose ethnic
origin. Offers were made to 301 women.
This is the second time in just over a year that the Bar has been involved
in a row over race discrimination. Last year it was accused of
discriminating against ethnic minority candidates in marking its finals
examination. An inquiry set up by the Bar school found no evidence of direct
discrimination.
The new selection system was introduced because too many students were
qualifying on academic grounds for a place on the finals course. Part of the
Bar's problem, however, is that its finals course is available only through
the Bar school.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, has condemned this
monopoly on training barristers as anti-competitive.
A Bar report on barrister's training to be published later this week is
expected to acknowledge that it may now have to validate courses at other
centres already licensed to run the solicitors' vocational course.
</TEXT>
