<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Payouts challenge allowed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The TUC and 10 unions yesterday won the right to bring a legal challenge to
government plans to reform the criminal injuries compensation system. It
intends to replace individual assessments with a fixed tariff from April 1.
Mr Justice Owen granted leave in the High Court for the unions to bring
judicial review proceedings and said the hearing should take place as soon
as possible.
Mr Guy Sankey, QC for Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, said the
application was misconceived. But he did not oppose the application for
leave as he accepted there was an arguable issue of public interest.
He gave an assurance that no final award would be made to any claimant until
the courts had decided the matter.
Mr Andrew Dismore, solicitor for the TUC and the unions, said: 'The unions
are very concerned about the effect on their members who face daily risks of
being attacked in their jobs.'
