<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Rifkind joins privacy campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The furore over the recent resignation of Air Marshal Sir Peter Harding as
chief of defence staff has won an influential convert to the cause of
privacy legislation.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, has decided that the government
should push for privacy laws even if it risks a head-on clash with the
press.
Mr Rifkind is understood to think the security angle used by some newspapers
to justify dwelling on the affair is preposterous.
The government has been determined for some time to introduce criminal
offences for electronic eavesdropping and the use of long-range lenses to
take photographs on private property. These would apply to everyone, and not
just to journalists.
But its original timetable has been subject to numerous delays. It could be
summer before a white paper is published - nearly a year after it was
promised.
The prime minister may, however, decide not to include new privacy measures
in the 1994-95 legislative timetable, in line with a strategy of shelving
radical legislation being urged on him by an influential group of cabinet
ministers.
Sir Peter resigned earlier this month after a newspaper alleged that he was
having an affair with the former wife of a retired Conservative politician.
</TEXT>
