<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Householders get free legal service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A free legal service has been launched for people living in an area of
Newcastle upon Tyne where harassment, vandalism and other crime has
frightened local residents and driven some from their homes.
The service, set up by Newcastle solicitors Pearson &amp; Caulfield, has been
initiated by Newcastle City Challenge and funded by a Pounds 30,000 grant
from a charitable trust, which requested anonymity.
Mr Jonathan Blackie, Newcastle director of City Challenge, the
government-backed scheme to regenerate urban areas, said he believed the
problems which north Benwell had faced in the last few years were
unparalleled in an area with mixed, predominantly privately-owned, housing.
He said the free legal service would use every device within the law to take
action against criminals.
It will help residents take legal action against the effects of crime and
harassment, and against absent owners and landlords of derelict property,
anti-social residents and statutory bodies if they fail to take necessary
action. This could include Northumbria police and Newcastle city council.
Leaflets about the service, to be launched officially on Monday, are being
circulated to all 2,500 North Benwell residents.
Mr Blackie said: 'We believe it's the first time the residents of an area
have been offered a completely free legal service to tackle their particular
problems.'
North Benwell's difficulties have caused property values to fall, leaving
some owner-occupiers trapped.
</TEXT>
