<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Banks clash on role of managers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The future of Britain's bank managers became an issue between two of the
largest high street banks last night, as Sir Brian Pearse, Midland chief
executive, underlined their continuing importance.
His remarks came just two days after Mr Martin Taylor, Barclays chief
executive, signalled the increasing role of technology in providing customer
services, such as loan decisions.
In a speech as president of the Institute of Bankers, Sir Brian said he
disagreed with the feeling that lay behind the suggestion that most credit
decisions could be handled by computers.
He said: 'Everywhere I go, customers, professional advisers and the media
bewail the fact that good experienced people are no longer available locally
to discuss problems and seek solutions.'
Sir Brian used the role of the bank manager as an example in his argument
that the main clearing banks were very different in their outlooks. Mr
Taylor had suggested that while people wanted to spend a lot of time with
the 'old-fashioned bank manager of myth' they did not want to pay for doing
so, and that there were not enough skilled staff to go through applications
in the way they used to do.
During the course of last year, Midland put more than 200 senior managers
back into the field. Sir Brian, who is about to retire as Midland chief
executive, said there had been 'a substantial increase' in new business
approaches.
In response to reports of Mr Taylor's comments, Mr Brian Pitman, chief
executive of Lloyds bank, said there was a large task in re-skilling bank
staff, but suggestions of the 'death of the bank manager' sounded slightly
premature.
A one-day strike at Girobank planned for today has been called off after an
improved pay offer to staff.
The National Communications Union, with 2,500 members at the main Girobank
office in Bootle, Merseyside, and a further 1,000 members at other offices
across the country, is to ballot on the new offer.
</TEXT>
