<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Post Office to face strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Post Office faces disruption from three industrial disputes over the
coming weeks.
Engineering staff working for the Royal Mail in London voted yesterday to
strike over the proposed closure of half the capital's mechanised letter
offices, starting next month.
The Royal Mail's 5,000 engineering workers around the country are voting in
a strike ballot to oppose the transfer of its building engineering services
to a separate subsidiary company RoMEC. The result will be known next week.
London's main post office workers will strike on March 30 about post office
closures after a three-to-one majority vote in support of industrial action.
But the Royal Mail appears close to agreement with the Union of
Communication Workers on a revised productivity deal for workers after the
original one was rejected last month in a ballot.
Mr Steve Jones, Mount Pleasant sorting office branch secretary of the
National Communications Union, said yesterday: 'Post Office management have
misjudged the mood of our engineering membership about the closure of
mechanised sorting offices in London and we will shortly be issuing notice
of strike action.' He added: 'We would like to see a negotiated settlement,
however this does not seem likely.'
On a 60 per cent turnout, 56 per cent of London's engineering workers backed
industrial action while 82 per cent supported disruption short of an all-out
strike.
Royal Mail said last night that the NCU had 'no mandate' to call its London
engineers on strike and added there was 'no question of any of them being
made redundant'.
The NCU's Mr Jones said: 'We are, without doubt, faced with the most
comprehensive set of attacks we have ever faced. We simply cannot afford to
ignore the consequences of not responding to management's unnecessary and
unjustified actions. Any sign of weakness will see in its wake even greater
attacks on our jobs and conditions.'
The UCW is lobbying parliament on March 30 in support of London post office
counter staff and calling on the public to back their one-day strike.
</TEXT>
