FT  23 MAR 94 / Clarke stands by Budget increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, has reaffirmed that the economic recovery
will not be threatened by the tax increases announced in the Budget, which
are due to come in over the next two weeks.
In an article in House magazine, a weekly journal distributed in the Palace
of Westminster, Mr Clarke says he was right to introduce increases in
taxation and cuts in public spending in last November's unified Budget.
He says that he accepted at the time that there would be 'recriminations and
upset as April approached' and that people are still 'a bit shell-shocked'
after the experience of the past few years.
But he remains convinced that he was right to make the reduction in the
public sector borrowing requirement the cornerstone of his proposals.
He says: 'If I had not taken decisive action, confidence would have taken a
serious knock.
'The main topic of economic debate now would not be the outlook for economic
recovery but how much more I would need to raise taxes in the next Budget.
That would create unwelcome uncertainty for people planning their family
finances. And the markets would have judged that this government had lost
the ability to take tough decisions.'
Mr Clarke acknowledged that some areas of the economy faced an uncertain
future.
But he says that low inflation has been the most promising of all economic
indicators in recent months.
