<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Praise aids civil servants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A strong defence of the independence of the civil service from political
control was made yesterday by Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the
Treasury.
He told a conference organised by the Council of Civil Service Unions that
the civil service was 'the tangible expression of the public-sector ethic
and an asset of real value. I would be wholly opposed to any change which
undermined the enviable reputation of British civil servants for integrity
and political independence'.
Union leaders at the conference expressed pleasure at Mr Dorrell's comments
at a time of mounting criticism about alleged politicisation of the higher
reaches of the civil service.
Mr Dorrell denied that promotion in the civil service was made through
'political cronyism'. He said: 'It is the strength of the civil service
traditions of honesty and independence which make our democracy real.
'The civil service attracts and retains the loyalty of high-quality public
servants because they have the assurance that, as far as is possible in any
human institution, their prospects will be determined by their abilities.'
But he also emphasised the government would continue its policy of
contracting out services which would develop their businesses in competition
with the private sector.
Mr John Monks, the TUC's general secretary, endorsed the call for a new code
of ethics to protect civil servants from political pressures and to govern
their relationship with ministers.
</TEXT>
