<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 94 / Fed steers course between White House and markets: Michael
Prowse examines the background to Alan Greenspan's action to increase the
Fed funds rate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After keeping financial markets on tenterhooks for several hours yesterday,
Mr Alan Greenspan, Federal Reserve chairman, duly announced the expected
tightening of monetary policy.
A move by the Fed was seen by markets as almost certain following President
Bill Clinton's decision last week to summon Mr Greenspan to the White House
for talks on economic policy. Had the Fed not moved after the White House
meeting, it would have been accused of bowing to political pressure.
Long-term yields, already nearly 7 per cent, might have moved even higher -
something that would have upset both the Fed and the Clinton administration.
But the quarter point increase in the Federal funds rate to 3.5 per cent
signalled by Mr Greenspan was not exactly a decisive move. It was the
smallest increase the Fed could have announced. It was not accompanied, as
some analysts had hoped, by an increase in the discount rate which remains
at 3 per cent.
A rise in the latter, say to 3.5 per cent, would have created a bigger
splash. In US newspapers, discount rate changes make the front page while
quarter point shuffles in the Fed funds rate are buried in the business
sections.
Mr Greenspan is thus pursuing the same 'softly-softly' approach he adopted
when lowering rates during the recession. Yesterday's move followed rather
than led market expectations: three month Treasury bill rates, for example,
had already risen sharply.
But Fed-watchers were intrigued that Mr Greenspan, as in his first
tightening move on February 4, followed Bundesbank procedure in formally
announcing the increase in rates. In the past, the Fed has left financial
markets to work out for themselves whether a change in pressure on reserve
positions signals an increase in short-term rates.
The new approach seems designed to counter congressional criticism of Fed
secrecy. But one side-effect will be to increase greatly the volatility of
financial markets on the day when the Fed holds a meeting of its
policy-making open market committee. And it will not mollify leading
congressional Democrats, such as Mr Henry Gonzales, chairman of the house
banking committee, who last week described Fed policy as a 'true
abomination'.
In financial markets, the immediate reaction to the Fed's announcement
yesterday was positive. Share and bond prices rose sharply, reflecting
relief that a debilitating period of uncertainty was over. But the relief
could prove short-lived.
After all, Mr Greenspan signalled in congressional testimony last month that
the Fed wanted to raise rates from the abnormally low levels of recent years
to a 'neutral' level - one consistent with sustainable non-inflationary
growth. Given an underlying inflation rate of 2.5-3 per cent, a neutral
level of short-term rates is generally taken to be about 4-5 per cent. Until
short-term rates reach this level financial markets are likely to remain
jittery, constantly wondering when the next rate increase will be announced.
'It is unlikely that this marks the conclusion of a move to a neutral
policy,' said Mr John Lipsky, chief economist at Salomon Brothers, the New
York brokerage. In his view, the way to ease bond market jitters is to raise
rates rapidly to about 4 per cent. Having moved decisively, the Fed could
then afford to sit back and see if it had done enough to convince markets it
was serious about controlling inflation.
'This is not enough,' says Mr Mickey Levy, chief economist at NationsBank in
New York. He believes further rate increases will be needed in coming months
to cool an economy that has acquired 'significant momentum'.
Recently revised figures showed the economy grew at an annual rate of 7.5
per cent in real terms in the fourth quarter of last year. And a raft of
data in the past few weeks - from car sales to industrial production -
suggest that the pace of growth remains robust in the first quarter of this
year, despite the adverse impact of severe winter weather.
But while a more decisive tightening of monetary policy might be the best
way to allay fears in financial markets and thus bring down long bond
yields, Mr Greenspan may feel he cannot afford to ignore the views of the
Clinton administration which has still to fill two vacant seats on the Fed's
seven-member board of governors.
The White House has argued repeatedly that inflation pressures are minimal,
implying that it sees little rationale for further increases in rates.
Yesterday, perhaps trying to make amends for the confusion in markets
created by Mr Clinton's ill-timed meeting with Mr Greenspan, the Treasury
issued a short statement reiterating its support for Fed independence. 'The
administration and the Fed have the same objective: sustainable economic
growth and low inflation,' it said.
However, administration economic forecasts last month were based on the
assumption that short-term interet rates would average 3.4 per cent this
year. The tightening of policy announced by Mr Greenspan yesterday means
this target rate has already been exceeded.
It is thus safe to predict a period of continuing tension between the White
House and the Fed, protestations of cordiality notwithstanding.
</TEXT>
