<PROFILE>_AN-ECVCOAG0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940322
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Survey of Jersey (3): Growth centre of finance industry -
There are now some 760 separate investment pools, many of them tied together
under umbrella structures / Fund Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Collective funds moved to the growth centre of Jersey's finance industry
last year, gaining from the big rises in most of the world's securities
markets and the parallel loss of appeal of bank deposits.
At the end of December, Jersey-based funds were worth Pounds 23.4bn; up 48
per cent in 12 months. Of the total, Pounds 19.5bn was accounted for by
open-ended funds and the remaining Pounds 3.9bn by closed-end vehicles.
There are now some 760 separate investment pools, many of them tied together
under umbrella structures.
Jersey's funds are largely invested in equities, reflecting a different
approach and clientele from that of, say, Luxembourg, which is heavily
orientated towards bonds. Just under 30 per cent of Jersey's open-ended fund
assets are bonds, with another 7 per cent in money funds. Equity funds are
mainly orientated towards Europe and the Far East.
The figures, incidentally, do not cover private funds, including offshore
institutional vehicles. These 'Cobo' funds, so-called because they are set
up only under the control of borrowing law rather than the collective
investment funds legislation, could be worth another Pounds 10bn, industry
experts say, although no statistics are available.
A survey published last month by accountants Coopers &amp; Lybrand showed,
unsurprisingly, that members of the Jersey Fund Managers Association are in
a buoyant mood. Some 84 per cent recorded higher profits in 1993, and 80 per
cent expect more gains in 1994.
The survey suggested that the industry was looking equally to three sources
of business - the retail market, institutional investors and private
portfolio management. Four geographical client categories were picked out:
the UK, UK expatriates, the Far East and the European Union, ranked in that
order of importance.
The importance of the UK market exposes the Jersey fund management industry
to the consequences of mainland regulatory changes, so local managers are
closely watching the proposals for the introduction of open-ended investment
companies (oeics) in the UK and accompanying changes such as the
introduction of single pricing.
Although oeics already exist in Jersey along with unit trusts, access to the
UK market is through designated territory status under Section 87 of the
Financial Services Act, a route which at present rules out single pricing.
'An area of concern is whether funds from the designated territories will be
required to be equivalent to unit trusts or to the new oeics,' says Mr
Jonathan Overland, spokesman for the JFMA and a marketing executive at
Capital House. There have been talks with the Treasury and the Securities
and Investments Board in the UK.
Access to other markets is clearly important to Jersey's future as an
offshore centre, and the authorities have been talking to several
jurisdictions. So far, Japan, Ireland, Switzerland and the Netherlands have
granted at least restricted or fund-by-fund marketing rights.
'We are all looking over our shoulders to se what happens on oeics,' says Mr
Alastair Torvaney, who runs Perpetual's Dollars 400m Jersey offshoot.
Mr Torvaney thinks individual deals with countries will prove costly and
time-consuming, however. In the meantime, he perceives opportunities for
third-party administration, for example for institutional funds which do not
require day-to-day attention. 'All retail funds in Jersey must be looking at
this as an add-on,' he says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6722 Management Investment, Open-End.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MKTS  Market shares.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
