<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Oils on the alert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO, PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The oil sectors provided the market's two highest turnover stocks in BP and
Lasmo, ahead of what is viewed by oil analysts as a crucial Opec meeting in
Geneva on Friday.
Oil specialists were saying yesterday that stories emanating from the Middle
East suggested that the most likely outcome of the talks was a roll-over of
the current output agreement for a further two quarters.
'If that is the case then there is probably scope for a further Dollars 1
slide in oil prices to around the Dollars 12.50 a barrel level,' said one
analyst.
BP was the market's biggest turnover stock with 7.6m traded, as the shares
edged up 3 1/2 to 371p as some of the market's action funds adopted an
aggressively positive view of Friday's Opec meeting.
Shell, on the other hand, dipped 2 1/2 to 670p, after talk of switching into
BP. Lasmo shares were sustained throughout the session, closing a penny
ahead at 131p on 7.2m traded following keen support by one of the big
international marketmaking firms. Lasmo is due to announce preliminary
figures tomorrow.
