<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow hurt by concerns over
monetary policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks fell sharply yesterday amid heightened international tensions and
nagging concerns over monetary policy, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 30.80 lower at 3,864.85,
surrendering all the gains it notched up in the previous session's
expiration-related rally. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was
down 2.52 at 468.54. In the secondary markets, the American SE composite was
off 2.19 at 470.77, while the Nasdaq composite, after setting two
consecutive all-time highs, fell 6.63 to 797.30.
NYSE activity was light, but a burst of program-driven selling at the
opening bell helped boost volume to 247m shares.
The optimistic note on which trading ended last week proved to be fleeting.
A primary concern yesterday was the failure of the US Treasury market to
staunch its losses after a sharp sell-off in the final trading day of last
week.
Today's meeting of the Federal Reserve's policy-making arm, the Federal Open
Market Committee, was weighing heavily on bonds. Prices dropped sharply
across the yield curve amid anticipation of an imminent move by the Fed to
nudge up short-term interest rates for a second time in as many months.
Political tensions were exacerbating the market's monetary jitters. Threats
by the US to take steps to punish North Korea for its refusal to permit
nuclear inspections accelerated a downward push in stocks that normally
follows big Friday advances.
Stocks which are sensitive to broad economic trends were among the big
losers. Chevron sagged Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 90 7/8 , Boeing shed Dollars
1 1/8 to Dollars 46, International Paper dropped Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 68
5/8 and 3M lost Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 102.
In banking, Baltimore Bancorp jumped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 19 1/4 after
First Fidelity offered to buy the group for Dollars 346m, or Dollars 20 3/4
a share.
Cadence Design Systems was up Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 15 3/8 in heavy
trading on the NYSE. The stock benefited from an upgrading by Mr Gregory
Gould, an analyst at Goldman Sachs in New York. IBM closed Dollars 1 1/4
ahead at Dollars 58 1/2 as analysts at a Phoenix trade convention
scrutinised computer operating software developed by its Taligent joint
venture with Apple.
Brazil
An unexpected rise in the benchmark overnight interest rate from 54 per cent
to 56.5 per cent, and rising inflation forecasts continued to take its toll
on the Sao Paulo stock market, where prices dropped 4.6 per cent in weak
trading. The Bovespa index ended at 12,708 points, down 610. Turnover was
Cr196.3bn (Dollars 243.8m).
State-run telecom firm Telebras fell 5 per cent, mining giant Vale do Rio
Doce was down down 4.9 per cent, and oil monopoly Petrobras dropped 7.1 per
cent.
Canada
Toronto stocks broke a six-day winning streak, closing sharply lower in
moderate trading. The TSE-300 index tumbled 43.11 points, or 0.94 per cent,
to 4,523.50, with declines leading advances 459 to 354 in decreased turnover
of CDollars 706.8m.
</TEXT>
