<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / International Company News: Allstate raises estimate of
California earthquake toll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The financial toll of January's earthquake in California seems set to rise
sharply to as much as Dollars 4bn, following yesterday's announcement by
another big US insurer that it has raised its estimate of losses.
Allstate, which has the second-biggest exposure to the earthquake, said it
now expected the disaster to cost it Dollars 600m, rather than the Dollars
350m it estimated before.
The increase followed an inspection of most of the 38,000 claims from
policyholders, the company said.
Another US insurer, 20th Century Insurance, said on Friday it expected the
earthquake to cost it Dollars 325m, more than double its original estimate
of Dollars 162m. The company, based in Los Angeles, warned that the costs
would wipe out around a quarter of its net worth.
Mr Jack Snyder, an insurance analyst at AM Best, the US ratings company,
said the two announcements reflected a general trend among US insurers to
revise their loss estimates upwards by between 50 and 100 per cent.
The revisions suggest that the total insured losses from the disaster, put a
month ago at around Dollars 2.5bn, are likely to be closer to Dollars 4bn,
he added.
Allstate put its market share of Californian homeowners insurance policies
at 15.6 per cent, behind State Farm, the market leader. State Farm has yet
to revise its expected losses, but the final cost to the company could reach
as much as Dollars 1bn, said Mr Snyder.
The higher level of losses is unlikely to be reflected in catastrophe
insurance premiums until the end of the year.
Allstate said the revision meant that it would report a pre-tax charge of
Dollars 750m in all in its first quarter results to reflect catastrophe
losses, with the remainder of the losses coming from bad weather.
The losses would result in an operating loss for the quarter of 30 cents a
share, and a net loss of around 15 cents a share.
Lloyd's of London said yesterday that the insurance payouts as a result of
the latest Los Angeles earthquake were unlikely to be large enough to
trigger any payments from its reinsurers, Andrew Jack adds from London.
It said that payments so far from London reinsurers from the Los Angeles
earthquake in January were Dollars 20m from non-marine and just Dollars
207,000 on aviation insurance policies.
These were only triggered once claims in the US on Los Angeles had risen
above Dollars 3bn.
Royal Insurance said it did not believe that many UK composite insurers
would be affected by yesterday's events.
</TEXT>
